        output='Based on the provided filing excerpts, here is what the document says regarding the AI segment\'s capital intensity, GPU investments, data center buildout, and overall capex outlook:\n\n### 1. AI Segment Capital Intensity\n* **Highly Capital-Intensive & Loss-Making:** The filing explicitly states that the AI segment (formed by the acquisition of xAI in February 2026) is "capital intensive" and has "incurred significant operating losses since inception." \n* **Multi-Year Horizon to Profitability:** The company expects a "multi-year investment horizon" before its massive infrastructure deployments translate into sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA. \n* **Cost of Compute Economics:** The cost of compute is identified as the primary driver of the "cost per token." The filing notes that for companies without a build-cost advantage, the total capital cost of compute infrastructure derives approximately **30% from data center construction** (shell, MEP, grid interconnection) and **70% from procuring processors and critical IT equipment**.\n* **Prioritizing Long-Term Growth:** Management warns that they may accelerate investments at any time, which "could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."\n\n### 2. GPU Infrastructure Investment\n* **Hardware Sourcing & Manufacturing:** The company is allocating substantial capital to specialized computing hardware, which includes both "obtaining third-party GPUs" and "manufacturing our own GPUs."\n* **Depreciation Driving Losses:** The massive scale of GPU procurement is heavily impacting the income statement. In Q1 2026, AI research and development expenses surged by $1.47 billion, and AI operating losses increased by $1.53 billion, both primarily driven by the **"depreciation of GPU hardware"** and cloud computing costs.\n* **Infrastructure as a Moat:** The filing asserts that frontier AI is "fundamentally infrastructure-constrained." Only operators with access to "very large GPU clusters" and massive power can train cutting-edge models, giving them non-linear performance advantages.\n* **Macro GPU Demand:** Citing industry estimates, the filing notes that global AI workload demand (estimated at 235 gigawatts by 2030) corresponds to a requirement of **104 million GPUs** (based on 1.3 kW per H100 SXM GPU).\n\n### 3. Data Center Buildout\n* **Rapid Terrestrial Expansion:** The company is aggressively investing in the "rapid expansion of our terrestrial data centers, including the development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure." \n* **Orbital Data Centers:** Looking to the future, the company plans to leverage its Starship launch vehicle to reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99%, establishing a scalable path to "launch orbital data centers" and create "orbital AI compute."\n* **Construction & Capitalized Interest:** "Construction in progress" on the balance sheet is heavily comprised of ongoing AI infrastructure and facilities not yet placed in service. The company capitalizes interest during the construction period for these significant, long-term AI data center projects.\n* **Global Infrastructure Constraints:** The filing contextualizes its buildout within a macro environment where meeting projected AI needs will require **$7 trillion in global data center investment through 2030**, with generative AI accounting for roughly 70% of total data-center power demand by the end of the decade.\n\n### 4. Capex Outlook\n* **Explosive Growth in AI Capex:** Capital expenditures for the AI segment have scaled dramatically:\n  * **2023:** $463 million\n  * **2024:** $5.63 billion\n  * **2025:** $12.72 billion\n  * **Q1 2026:** $7.72 billion (representing the vast majority of the company\'s $10.1 billion total quarterly capex).\n* **Scaling with Power and Compute:** The company states that during this investment period, capital expenditures **"will scale as quickly as we are able to deploy power and compute"** to capture an estimated $26.5 trillion total market opportunity for AI.\n* **Foreseeable Increases:** Management expects these costs to "continue to increase for the foreseeable future."\n* **Financing the Buildout:** To fund these massive capital requirements and maintain strong liquidity, the company plans to "access a range of debt and equity financing solutions available to us as a public company."',
